<item>
            <title>[TIKA-388] Don&apos;t trust streams that claim mark support</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/TIKA-388</link>
                <project id="12310631" key="TIKA">Tika</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;As seen on tika-dev@ and in &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/JCR-2576&quot; title=&quot;DbInputStream does not support mark()/reset() when exhausted.&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;JCR-2576&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;JCR-2576&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, there are some InputStream implementations that claim to support the mark feature, but lose the mark as soon as the end of stream has been reached. There&apos;s no way for a client to detect such behaviour, so it&apos;s probably best for Tika to always use BufferedInputStream to wrap incoming streams when mark support is needed. This may cause one layer of extra buffering, but avoids problems with such broken streams.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment></environment>
        <key id="12459494">TIKA-388</key>
            <summary>Don&apos;t trust streams that claim mark support</summary>
